      <p>Brisbane's inner east has seen a notable rise in buyer's agent activity over the past few years. Properties in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, and Camp Hill regularly attract offers submitted by buyer's agents representing purchasers who want professional representation in what is a competitive and often complex market. For vendors, this shift raises practical questions: Who pays the buyer's agent? Does their involvement change the negotiation? Should you treat a buyer's agent-represented offer differently from a direct buyer offer?</p>

      <p>The short answer to the last question is no, you should not. The offer is what matters, not who submitted it. But understanding how buyer's agents are paid and how the relationship between buyer's agents and listing agents works will make you a more informed seller.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyer's agents are paid</h2>
      <p>In the vast majority of cases in Queensland, the buyer's agent is paid by the buyer, not the seller. The most common fee structure is a percentage of the purchase price, typically in the range of 1.5% to 3% of the property value, charged directly to the buyer as their client. Some buyer's agents charge a flat fee or a retainer plus a success fee. As a seller, this cost is not your concern and does not come out of your proceeds.</p>

      <p>What this means practically is that when a buyer's agent submits an offer on your property, the offer price already reflects their client's total budget, including the commission that buyer will pay their agent. The presence of a buyer's agent does not inflate the offer price the buyer can afford to pay you. In some cases it may do the opposite, since buyers who have engaged a professional advocate may be more disciplined about what they are willing to bid.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Conjunctional arrangements and commission sharing</h2>
      <p>In some transactions, a conjunctional arrangement applies between the listing agent and the buyer's agent. Under this model, a portion of the listing agent's commission is shared with the buyer's agent in exchange for bringing the buyer to the property and facilitating the transaction. The commission split is agreed between the two agencies and does not change the amount you, as the seller, have agreed to pay your listing agent.</p>

      <p>Conjunctional arrangements are common in Queensland real estate, particularly for properties sold through private treaty. From a seller's perspective, the total commission figure on your Form 6 agreement with your listing agent is what you pay. The way that commission is distributed internally between agents is a matter for the agencies, not for you.</p>

      <p>Your listing agent is required to disclose any conjunctional arrangement to you, and you should be informed if a buyer's agent is involved in a transaction. This transparency is part of their professional obligation. If you have any questions about how a particular offer came to be and whether a conjunctional fee arrangement applies, ask your agent directly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a buyer's agent's involvement means for negotiation</h2>
      <p>Buyer's agents are professional negotiators who know how to structure offers, insert conditions, and advocate hard for their clients. This does not make them adversaries in a transaction. In fact, buyer's agent-represented transactions often proceed more smoothly than unrepresented ones, because the buyer's agent understands the process, manages their client's expectations, and facilitates clear communication between the parties.</p>

      <p>However, there are a few things sellers should be aware of. A buyer's agent will typically have done their homework on comparable sales, current market conditions, and what the property is genuinely worth. Their client will have a clear idea of the top of their budget. The offer you receive is likely to be considered rather than emotional. This means aggressive countering above market value is unlikely to be effective, while a clean offer at or slightly above a realistic price with straightforward conditions has a good chance of being accepted.</p>

      <p>Buyer's agents also tend to move quickly. If they have identified your property as the right fit for their client, they will want to secure it before their client sees something else. This can work in a seller's favour, particularly if you are trying to achieve a clean sale within a specific timeframe.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Assessing a buyer's agent-represented offer</h2>
      <p>When assessing an offer from a buyer represented by a buyer's agent, apply the same criteria you would to any other offer. Look at the price, the conditions, the finance clause (if any), the proposed settlement period, and the overall cleanliness of the contract. A strong offer from a buyer's agent-represented purchaser with finance pre-approval in place and a short due-diligence period is a compelling offer regardless of who submitted it.</p>

      <p>What you should not do is assume that because a buyer's agent is involved, there is more room to negotiate upward than with an unrepresented buyer. Buyer's agents typically have their clients on a defined budget and will walk away from a property that exceeds that budget rather than advise their client to overextend. Your listing agent is best placed to read the level of genuine interest behind a buyer's agent-represented offer and advise you on the right response.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why buyer's agent activity has grown in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>The growth in buyer's agent activity in suburbs like Bulimba, Hawthorne, and Morningside reflects a few converging factors. Properties in these suburbs are expensive, and many buyers are making once-in-a-generation purchasing decisions with significant sums. The cost of getting it wrong is high, and professional guidance is seen as worthwhile insurance. Interstate buyers relocating to Brisbane, and cashed-up locals who have sold in Sydney or Melbourne and are purchasing in Brisbane's inner east, are particularly likely to use buyer's agents to navigate a market they do not know intimately.</p>

      <p>For sellers, this increased activity is broadly positive. Buyer's agents bring motivated, pre-qualified clients who are ready to transact. Their presence in your market means there is a professional ecosystem helping buyers find and purchase properties like yours. A well-run campaign that attracts multiple buyer's agents and their clients creates genuine competition, which is what drives strong prices.</p>

